  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT344-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">piriviṭai vaṟpuṟuttun tōḻikkut talaimakaḷ kūriyatu. </p>


        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken by HER to the confidante who encourages [her] in
          the time of separation. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT344">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> nōṟṟōr maṉṟa tōḻi taṇṇeṉat</l>
          <l> tūṟṟun tuvalaip paṉikkaṭun tiṅkaṭ</l>
          <l> pulampayi rarunta vaṇṇa lēṟoṭu</l>
          <l> nilantūṅ kaṇala vīṅkumulaic ceruttal</l>
          <l> pālvār kuḻavi yuḷḷi niraiyiṟan</l>
          <l> tūrvayiṟ peyarum puṉkaṇ mālai</l>
          <l> yarumpeṟaṟ poruṭpiṇip pōkip</l>
          <l> pirintuṟai kātalar varakkāṇ pōrē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Penance have they done indeed, friend,</l>
          <l>who see the long  <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">  pirintu uṟai </term>: here the durative function of the auxiliary. </note>  -separated lover coming,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">having gone enticed by wealth difficult to obtain,</l>
          <l rend="indent">at sorrowful evening, when those with dewlaps <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta">	aṇala </term> "those with dewlaps" (aṇal DEDR 114 "dewlap"), is probably a pan-Indian designation for the cow. Thus also Cām.; different L./Sh.P., who take <term xml:lang="ta"> ceruttal </term>, "udder", as a word for cow.   </note> </l>
          <l rend="indent8">hanging to the ground,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">traversing the row  <note place="foot"> That is, the mother-cows go in front. The sequence of absolutives in this line (<term xml:lang="ta">vārpu...uḷḷi...iṟantu</term>) is not well-formed in such a way as to be construable with <term xml:lang="ta"> aṇala </term> as a subject. <term xml:lang="ta"> uḷḷi </term> and <term xml:lang="ta"> iṟantu </term> certainly evoke the formulaic <term xml:lang="ta"> uḷḷar kollō...iṟantōrē </term>, i.e. HIS memory of HER.  </note>   in remembrance of [their] calves,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">milk flowing over from udders with swelling teats,</l>
          <l rend="indent">are returning to the village</l>
          <l rend="indent2">with [their] majestic bull, as they eat <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> arunta </term>, infinitive, is difficult to construe here. For one thing, it has obviously the same subject as the row of absolutives + <term xml:lang="ta"> peyareccam </term>, namely the herd of cows. Secondly, we would expect a form capable of expressing temporal anteriority here, because the cows return to the village after having eaten corn in the fields. Probably the best solution is to take it as an atemporal description of the situation during the rainy season: this is what cows do during that period. </note> of the corn from the fields,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">in the month of heavy dew with drops spreading coolly.</l>


        </lg>
      </div>
